				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: A couple of stupid questions<a name="6473"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Apr 18 03 2:52 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Well, lvl 21 is fairly easy to get.  If you don't mind spending the extra time to get lvl 21 back, and the money to buy back all the songs again... you will benefit in the long run.  It all depends on how far you want to take your bard.  If you only plan to casually play, then by all means, just have fun and play your bard to the best of his/her abilities.  If you are looking to make the best bard with perfect raiding stats, then I'd suggest putting all your points into sta to give yourself an edge over most bards in terms of hps.  
<br />

<br />
But believe me, all in all, it doesn't really matter.  I play a high end cleric as my main, as well as a ranger.  My cleric was my first character, and I didn't put 1 point into WIS.  I knew nothing about EQ when I made him.  He has 100str and 100sta as his base.  I constantly kick myself for not giving him any WIS because I have to sacrafice good gear with better overall stats for WIS gear to stay at 255 wis.  But when it comes down to it, if you play your character well, and are a nice, courteous player, stats don't matter at all.  I've found that this is a game of friends.  Yes, having great stats is nice, but isn't the most important part of the game.  Even though I screwed up the stats on my cleric, he is still a good cleric.  I'm rambling now, so just decide if the pro's outweigh the cons of re-rolling your bard.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
